%I A393127 #19 Mar 30 2026 17:35:29
%S A393127 1,5,7,14,26,26,5,92,54,30,36,224,39,378,560,51,1246,1130,1798,1561
%N A393127 Least m such that 10^A393126(n) - 1 - 10^m is a reversible prime (emirp or palindromic prime).
%C A393127 The lesser of the two emirps is A004086(10^k - 1 - 10^m) = 10^k - 1 - 10^(k-m-1), k = A393126(n). When a(n) = m = (k-1)/2, we have a palindromic ("wing") prime.
%C A393127 See the main entry A393126 for more information.
%F A393127 1 <= a(n) <= (A393126(n) - 1)/2, for all n.
%o A393127 (PARI) A393127(n)=is_A393126(A393126[n]) \\ if A393126 is a precomputed list - there is no efficient function A393126(n).
%Y A393127 Cf. A393126, A006567 (emirps), A004086 (digit reversal).
%Y A393127 Cf. A020472 (primes with only digits 8 and 9), A173594 (near-repdigit emirps), A128389 (emirps with only composite digits).
%Y A393127 Cf. A263431 (near-repdigit primes with only digits 9 and a single 8).
%K A393127 nonn,base,more,new
%O A393127 1,2
%A A393127 _M. F. Hasler_, Mar 23 2026
%E A393127 a(15)-a(20) from _Michael S. Branicky_, Mar 24 2026
